@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

AG2HH is a tool to convert standard @{amigaguide} documents into Maxon's
HotHelp format.@{par}

It does @{b}not @{ub}only create simple header files like Maxon's EasyHotHelp
does, instead it really converts the whole text! This gives you the
ability to edit the final output and add some special HotHelp features,
eg. graphics or something.@{par}

AG2HH is @{b}VERY @{ub}fast! On my machine (A1200/030/50) it converts the GoldED
4.6.0 manual (356261 bytes) in 14.8 seconds, which is an overall speed of
476 lines/s or 24072 bytes/s.@{par}

Note that you also need the HotHelpComp compiler. This will not be provided
within this archive.@{par}


  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}68020+ versions@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

Please do @{b}not @{ub}ask for special compiled versions for 68020+ CPUs!
Whenever a new version is finished I do some Benchmark tests on my
machine.@{par}

In version 2.0, a 68020 version gives a speed gain of ~2.405% on my
computer, that is only ~1.048 seconds per MByte!@{par}
(Also tested with the GoldED 4.5.1 manual.)@{par}

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

AG2HH can only be used from the Shell:@{par}

  @{lindent 2}@{i}AG2HH <input file> <output file> [-p <preferences file>] [-a] [-ak]
[-np] [-nw] [-q] @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}

AG2HH will take the input file in @{amigaguide} format and creates the output
file in Maxon's HotHelp format. If the output file already exists, it will
be overwritten without @{"warnings" link "Warnings"}.@{par}

@{b}Parameters: @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-p   @{ui}Specify the path to a standard HotHelpCompiler.Pref file as created by
     HotHelpComp.@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-a   @{ui}Switch AutoDoc mode on. Whenever a reference contains a pair of brackets
("@{fg highlight}()@{fg text}") at its end, these brackets will, of course, be stripped. If you switch
AutoDoc mode on, AG2HH will output "@{fg highlight}()@{fg text}" right behind the reference.@{par}
For example, "@{fg highlight}\@{"  test()  " link ...}@{fg text}" would become
"@{fg highlight}|QV|test|QV|()@{fg text}" instead of only "@{fg highlight}|QV|test|QV|@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-ak  @{ui}Switch AutoKeys mode on. See below for details.@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-np  @{ui}Suppress progress display only.@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-nw  @{ui}Suppress warnings only.@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 5}@{i}-q   @{ui}Suppress all visual output.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Example invocations: @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}- Convert; use user preferences:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{lindent 4}@{i}AG2HH MyProject.guide MyProject.txt -p Prefs/HotHelpCompiler.Pref @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 2}- Convert; use standard codes, AutoDoc mode, no progress display:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{lindent 4}@{i}AG2HH MyProject.guide MyProject.txt -a -np @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}


  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}AutoKeys mode@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

As you might know from the original @{amigaguide} system, you can create
links with totally different labels than their referenced nodes.@{par}

For example, you can link a button with the label "foo" to the node "bar".
A second button named "foobar" could also be linked to the node "bar".@{par}

In HotHelp, this is not possible. Kind of stupid, huh?
Who knows why...@{par}

This is where AG2HH's AutoKeys mode can help. It creates invisible keys
inside the destination entries. In the above example, it would not only create
the key "bar" as usual, but also "foo" and "foobar".@{par}

You should always use the -ak parameter to get the best results.@{par}

Note that using the -ak parameter needs two passes of processing the
input file.@{par}


  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}Notes on usage@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

Most errors during compilation of converted documents only show up
because of misunderstandings by HotHelpComp.@{par}

For example, if a converted document contains the text "@{fg highlight}|QV|GT|QV|@{fg text}",
one would assume a reference to the entry "GT". Unfortunately, HotHelpComp
fails to compile the source code because it finds a "@{fg highlight}|GT|@{fg text}" for some reason,
which is a command like "@{fg highlight}|QV|@{fg text}".@{par}

Because of those stupid bugs in HotHelpComp, it is really important that
you use custom settings that can never ever interfer with HotHelpComp's
assumptions!@{par}

In the AG2HH archive you will find a preferences file for HotHelpComp.
I used the syntax "@{fg highlight}<<<@{b}@{fg fill}COMMAND@{fg highlight}@{ub}>>>@{fg text}"
in it, so you will hopefully never find any @{amigaguide} documents using such
weird texts...@{par}

@endnode
@node "Commands" "Commands"
@{par}
  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}General information@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{fg highlight}Note that this section only uses the default preferences as they are shipped @{fg text}
@{fg highlight}together with the HotHelp system from Maxon. You can always set your own @{fg text}
@{fg highlight}@{"preferences" link "Preferences"} by using the -p @{"parameter" link "Usage"}.@{fg text}@{par}

All entry names and reference labels will be cut down to the maximum size
of 49 characters. Additionally, the illegal characters "@{fg highlight}?%#|()[]\\*@{b}@{fg fill}<TAB>@{ub}@{fg text}"
(not including the first and last quote) will be filtered out (for autodocs,
have a look at the -a parameter). Furthermore, all leading and trailing whitespaces
must be filtered out, eg. "@{fg highlight}  text()  @{fg text}" becomes
"@{fg highlight}text@{fg text}".@{par}

Whenever there is a "@{fg highlight}/*@{fg text}", a "@{fg highlight}*/@{fg text}" or a "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" within your text (also not
including all first and last quotes), you will get a warning. These are
HotHelp commands for building context and line-oriented comments. If you
don't want them to become invisible in your final HotHelp project, you
should change your HotHelpComp settings.@{par}
The warning can be suppressed using the -nw switch at the AG2HH command
line.@{par}

All commands will be treated as case-insensitive, except "@{fg highlight}\@$VER:@{fg text}".
This means that, for example, "@{fg highlight}\@endnode@{fg text}" is equal to "@{fg highlight}\@EndNode@{fg text}".@{par}


  @{b}@{u}Commands@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

This section describes the @{amigaguide} commands and how they are handled
by AG2HH.@{par}

@{b}\@node <name> [<title>] @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@dnode <name> [<title>] @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}These both lines will get converted into invisible keys:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}|U-SCHL|<name>|U-SCHL|@{fg text}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}Note that the special entry name "Main" (case-insensitive) will become@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}|U-SCHL|Startseite|U-SCHL|@{fg text}@{par}

@{b}\@endnode @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}This line gets converted to an end-of-entry marker:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}-*-*-*-*-*-@{fg text}@{par}

@{b}\@rem <remark> @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@remark <remark> @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}This line-oriented remark will be converted into this:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{lindent 4}@{fg highlight}// <remark>@{fg text}@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}\@{<label> link <node> [<line>]} @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{<label> alink <node> [<line>]} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}These two commands will be converted into references:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}|QV|<label>|QV|@{fg text}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}As you can see, the visible button @{b}label @{ub}is used to create a reference.
This way, you don't have to modify your reference labels.@{par}
It is recommended that you use the -ak parameter.@{par}

@{settabs 25 50}@{b}\@{b} @{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{i} @{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{u} @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{ub} @{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{ui} @{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{uu} @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{plain} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}These commands will be converted into their corresponding style commands
("@{fg highlight}|SCHR-1|@{fg text}" through "@{fg highlight}|SCHR-8|@{fg text}").@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}\@{amigaguide} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}This command will be converted into the following text:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}AmigaGuide®@{fg text} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}(including the bold style)@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}\@{par} @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{line} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}This will be converted into:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}|ABS|@{fg text}@{par}

@{b}\@{body} @{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{code} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}These will be converted into:@{lindent 0}@{par}
    @{fg highlight}|FL|@{fg text}@{par}

@{b}\@{lindent <width>} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}A line containing this command will not be modified, but all following
lines will be indented by <width> spaces.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}\@{tab} @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}A TAB character (ASCII code 9) will be output.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}All other unknown commands are simply filtered out. @{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "Preferences" "Preferences"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Preferences@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

Since version 1.1, AG2HH is able to import standard HotHelpCompiler.Pref
as they are created by HotHelpComp.@{par}

If you do not specify the -p @{"parameter" link "Usage"} on the command line, AG2HH will
use the default HotHelpComp preferences as they are shipped with the
HotHelp system from Maxon.@{par}

@endnode
@node "Warnings" "Warnings"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Warnings@{uu} @{ub}@{par}

Note that you can switch off all warnings using the -nw or the -q @{"switches" link "Usage"}.@{par}

@{b}Empty entry label @{ub}@{par}
  @{lindent 2}After stripping away all illegal characters from an entry label, the entry
label is illegally empty.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Illegal entry label @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  After stripping away all illegal characters from an entry label, the entry
label illegally starts with one of the characters "@{fg highlight}0@{fg text}"-"@{fg highlight}9@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Empty reference label @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  After stripping away all illegal characters of a reference label, the
reference label is illegally empty.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Illegal reference label @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  After stripping away all illegal characters of a reference label, the
reference label illegally starts with one of the characters "@{fg highlight}0@{fg text}"-"@{fg highlight}9@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Possible // comment error @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  A "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file. If you didn't change your
preferences, this could introduce unwanted comments in the output file.@{par}
Note: This warning will not appear if you use the -p parameter!@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Possible /* */ comment error @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  A "@{fg highlight}/*@{fg text}" or "@{fg highlight}*/@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file. If you didn't
change your preferences, this could introduce unwanted comments in the
output file.@{par}
Note: This warning will not appear if you use the -p parameter!@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}Comment found and converted @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}  A "@{fg highlight}\@remark@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file and was converted
to a "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" sequence.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode

